7 less than six months or six months or more and less than or equal to
8 twelve months or two thousand eighty hours or (ii) a grant-funded
9 position or a special project.
10 (5)(a) Within the first one hundred eighty days of employment, a
11 full-time employee may apply to the board for vesting credit for years of
12 participation in another Nebraska governmental plan, as defined by
13 section 414(d) of the Internal Revenue Code. During the years of
14 participation in the other Nebraska governmental plan, the employee must
15 have been a full-time employee, as defined in the Nebraska governmental
16 plan in which the credit was earned. The board may adopt and promulgate
17 rules and regulations governing the assessment and granting of vesting
18 credit.
19 (b) If the contributory retirement plan or contract let pursuant to
20 section 48-609, as such section existed prior to January 1, 2018, is
21 terminated, employees of the Department of Labor who are active
22 participants in such contributory retirement plan or contract on the date
23 of termination of such plan or contract shall be granted vesting credit
24 for their years of participation in such plan or contract.
25 (6) Any employee who qualifies for membership in the retirement
26 system pursuant to this section may not be disqualified for membership in
27 the retirement system solely because such employee also maintains
28 separate employment which qualifies the employee for membership in
29 another public retirement system, nor may membership in this retirement
30 system disqualify such an employee from membership in another public
31 retirement system solely by reason of separate employment which qualifies
-99-

LB820 LB820
2026 2026
1 such employee for membership in this retirement system.
2 (7) State agencies shall ensure that employees authorized to
3 participate in the retirement system pursuant to this section shall
4 enroll and make required contributions to the retirement system
5 immediately upon becoming an employee. Information necessary to determine
6 membership in the retirement system shall be provided by the employer.
7 Sec. 47. Section 84-1503, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
8 amended to read:
9 84-1503 (1) It shall be the duty of the Public Employees Retirement
10 Board:
11 (a) To administer the retirement systems provided for in the County
12 Employees Retirement Act, the Judges Retirement Act, the Nebraska State
13 Patrol Retirement Act, the School Employees Retirement Act, the State
14 Employees Retirement Act, and , beginning September 1, 2024, the Class V
15 School Employees Retirement Act. The agency for the administration of the
16 retirement systems and under the direction of the board shall be known
17 and may be cited as the Nebraska Public Employees Retirement Systems;
18 (b) To appoint an executive a director to administer the systems
19 under the direction of the board. The appointment shall be subject to the
20 approval of the Governor and a majority of the Legislature. Executive
21 director Director qualifications shall include, but not be limited to,
22 (i) supervisory or management experience and (ii) training in, experience
23 with, or a demonstrated knowledge of qualified public employee retirement
24 plan administration. The executive director shall not be a member of the
25 board. The salary of the executive director shall be set by the board.
26 The executive director shall serve without term and may be removed by the
27 board;
28 (c) To provide for an equitable allocation of expenses among the
29 retirement systems administered by the board, and all expenses shall be
30 provided from the investment income earned by the various retirement
31 funds unless alternative sources of funds to pay expenses are specified
-100-

LB820 LB820
2026 2026
1 by law;
2 (d) To administer the deferred compensation program authorized in
3 section 84-1504;
4 (e) To hire an attorney to advise the board in the administration of
5 the retirement systems listed in subdivision (a) of this subsection. The
6 attorney shall be admitted to practice law in Nebraska, except that the
7 board shall have the discretion to hire an attorney for a probationary
8 period not to exceed six months pending such attorney's admission to
9 practice law in Nebraska;
10 (f) To hire an internal auditor to perform the duties described in
11 section 84-1503.04 who meets the minimum standards as described in
12 section 84-304.03; and
13 (g) To adopt and implement procedures for reporting information by
14 employers, as well as testing and monitoring procedures in order to
15 verify the accuracy of such information. The information necessary to
16 determine membership shall be provided by the employer. The board may
17 adopt and promulgate rules and regulations and prescribe such forms
18 necessary to carry out this subdivision. Nothing in this subdivision
19 shall be construed to require the board to conduct onsite audits of
20 political subdivisions for compliance with statutes, rules, and
21 regulations governing the retirement systems listed in subdivision (1)(a)
22 of this section regarding membership and contributions.
23 (2) In administering the retirement systems listed in subdivision
24 (1)(a) of this section, it shall be the duty of the board:
25 (a) To determine, based on information provided by the employer, the
26 prior service annuity, if any, for each person who is an employee of the
27 county on the date of adoption of the retirement system;
28 (b) To determine the eligibility of an individual to be a member of
29 the retirement system and other questions of fact in the event of a
30 dispute between an individual and the individual's employer;
31 (c) To adopt and promulgate rules and regulations, as the board may
-101-

LB820 LB820
2026 2026
1 deem necessary, for the management of the board;
2 (d) To keep a complete record of all proceedings taken at any
3 meeting of the board;
4 (e) To obtain, by a competitive, formal, and sealed bidding process
5 through the materiel division of the Department of Administrative
6 Services, actuarial services on behalf of the State of Nebraska as may be
7 necessary in the administration and development of the retirement
8 systems, including, but not limited to, preparation of an annual
9 actuarial valuation report of each of the defined benefit and cash
10 balance plans administered by the board. Such annual valuation reports
11 shall be presented by the actuary to the Nebraska Retirement Systems
12 Committee of the Legislature at a public hearing or hearings. Any
13 contract for actuarial services shall contain a provision allowing the
14 actuary, without prior approval of the board, to perform actuarial
15 studies of the systems as requested by entities other than the board, if
16 notice, which does not identify the entity or substance of the request,
17 is given to the board, all costs are paid by the requesting entity,
18 results are provided to the board, the Nebraska Retirement Systems
19 Committee of the Legislature, and the Legislative Fiscal Analyst upon
20 being made public, and such actuarial studies do not interfere with the
21 actuary's ongoing responsibility to the board. The term of the contract
22 shall be for up to three years. A competitive, formal, and sealed bidding
23 process shall be completed at least once every three years, unless the
24 board determines that such a process would not be cost effective under
25 the circumstances and that the actuarial services performed have been
26 satisfactory, in which case the contract may also contain an option for
27 renewal without a competitive, formal, and sealed bidding process for up
28 to two additional three-year periods. An actuary under contract for the
29 State of Nebraska shall be a member of the American Academy of Actuaries
30 and meet the academy's qualification standards to render a statement of
31 actuarial opinion;
-102-

LB820 LB820
2026 2026
1 (f) To direct the State Treasurer to transfer funds, as an expense
2 of the retirement systems, to the Legislative Council Retirement Study
3 Fund. Such transfer shall be in such amounts as the Legislature shall
4 direct;
5 (g) To adopt and promulgate rules and regulations, as the board may
6 deem necessary, to carry out the provisions of each retirement system
7 described in subdivision (1)(a) of this section, which includes, but is
8 not limited to, the crediting of military service, direct rollover
9 distributions, and the acceptance of rollovers;
10 (h) To obtain auditing services for a separate compliance audit of
11 the retirement systems to be completed by December 31, 2028, and from
12 time to time at the request of the Nebraska Retirement Systems Committee
13 of the Legislature, to be completed not more than every four years but
14 not less than every ten years. The compliance audit shall be in addition
15 to the annual audit conducted by the Auditor of Public Accounts. The
16 compliance audit shall include, but not be limited to, an examination of
17 records, files, and other documents and an evaluation of all policies and
18 procedures to determine compliance with all state and federal laws. A
19 copy of the compliance audit shall be given to the Governor, the board,
20 and the Nebraska Retirement Systems Committee of the Legislature and
21 shall be presented to the committee at a public hearing;
22 (i) To adopt and promulgate rules and regulations, as the board may
23 deem necessary, for the adjustment of contributions or benefits, which
24 includes, but is not limited to: (i) The procedures for refunding
25 contributions, adjusting future contributions or benefit payments, and
26 requiring additional contributions or repayment of benefits; (ii) the
27 process for a member, member's beneficiary, employee, or employer to
28 dispute an adjustment to contributions or benefits; (iii) establishing
29 materiality and de minimus amounts for agency transactions, adjustments,
30 and inactive account closures; and (iv) notice provided to all affected
31 persons. Following an adjustment, a timely notice shall be sent that
-103-

LB820 LB820
2026 2026
1 describes the adjustment and the process for disputing an adjustment to
2 contributions or benefits;
3 (j)(i) To amend the deferred compensation plan to require that in
4 the event of a member's death, except as provided in section 42-1107, the
5 death benefit shall be paid to the following, in order of priority:
6 (A) To the member's surviving designated beneficiary on file with
7 the board;
8 (B) To the spouse married to the member on the member's date of
9 death if there is no surviving designated beneficiary on file with the
10 board; or
11 (C) To the member's estate if the member is not married on the
12 member's date of death and there is no surviving designated beneficiary
13 on file with the board; and
14 (ii) The priority designations described in subdivision (2)(j)(i) of
15 this section shall not apply if the member has retired under a joint and
16 survivor benefit option;
17 (k) To make a thorough investigation through the executive director
18 or the executive director's designee, of any overpayment of a benefit,
19 when in the judgment of the executive director such investigation is
20 necessary, including, but not limited to, circumstances in which benefit
21 payments are made after the death of a member or beneficiary and the
22 retirement system is not made aware of such member's or beneficiary's
23 death. In connection with any such investigation, the board, through the
24 executive director or the executive director's designee, shall have the
25 power to compel the attendance of witnesses and the production of books,
26 papers, records, and documents, whether in hardcopy, electronic form, or
27 otherwise, and issue subpoenas for such purposes. Such subpoenas shall be
